							<h1>Chinatown Library</h1>
                                <audio src="/audio/en/library.mp3" controls>
                                Recording of Chicago Public Library Chinatown branch article
                                </audio>
								<p><br>The Chicago Public Library first opened a branch in Chinatown in 1972 and the community quickly started to use it as not just a learning resource, but as a community organizing space. <br> <br />
								In 1990, the branch moved to an 11,000 square foot rental space. While in that space, the Chinatown branch became the busiest branch of the Chicago Public Library system. <br> <br />
								With support from the community, elected officials, and branch staff, CPL contracted the architecture firm Skidmore, Owings, & Merrill to construct its current building. The two-story space was designed to be sustainable, featuring a solar shading screen integrated into the building’s exterior glass, causing it to use 30% less energy than a typical library. <br> <br />
								The Chinatown branch hosts a variety of educational, civic, and cultural programming. The children’s and teen’s programs focus on STEAM - science, technology, engineering, art, and mathematics. These programs range from reading programs, storytelling events, and technology workshops with 3D printers and high-end cameras. <br> <br />
								The branch also programs things unique to this community. Twice weekly, the branch showcases classical Cantonese opera. Local artists also shows work throughout the branch, rotating out exhibits four times a year. The branch is also home to groups of senior citizens, where friendly games of Mahjong and Chinese chess are commonplace. </p>
